Links between adipose tissue and thrombosis in the mouse.

Bodary PF(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Nutrition and Food Science, College of Liberal Arts and 
Sciences, Wayne State University, Detroit, Mich, USA. pfbodary@wayne.edu

Obesity has become a global epidemic and carries a considerable negative impact 
in regard to quality of life and life expectancy. A primary problem is that 
obese individuals are at increased risk of suffering from cardiovascular disease 
complications such as myocardial infarction and stroke. Because fat accumulation 
is a consistent aspect of obesity, mechanisms that may link adipose tissue to 
cardiovascular disease complications should be considered. Proteins expressed 
from adipose tissue, known as adipokines, are hypothesized to have important 
effects on the progression and incidence of cardiovascular disease 
complications. This review examines the evidence that adipokines play a direct 
role in vascular thrombosis, an important event in cardiovascular disease 
complications.

